snippet.textDisplay:
This is lit badly, I get what they're trying to do but they didn't do it well.

As for AJ saying he has no fear of that right hand 🤔, there isn't a man alive who doesn't know the danger that stick of dynamite comes with 🤷🏾‍♂️

Also he took a right hand off Wlad and went down. Deontay is a different type of puncher. So he definitely knows he can't get hit clean by him. As for saying he can control the ring with Wilder better than Ortiz man if he does that he definitely wins because Ortiz was no mug in both of those fights he gave a great account of himself it's just that he's a little too old to concentrate the same as he might've been able to before.

AJ is the man to beat for sure, he has the belts, the fans and is the face of the division. Wilder has one weapon and a punchers chance that he is not ashamed to let you know is all he needs. Could AJ avoid that sledgehammer right all night or put Deontay away with one of his own? That's why this fight will be one of the richest ever in boxing.

snippet.textDisplay: There is one thing for sure with AJ and Wilder don't take the 11/10 against on AJ or the 4/5 Wilder . The value will be in the round betting . All I know is it wouldn't go the distance and could go either way.  I think it will be a decent fight and could end before the 5th. That's the way I'm speculating . But I think that Tyson Fury will be AJ's next opponent (before Wilder) . AJ is not quite ready for Wilder and needs a few more rounds under His belt. And Tyso Fury has earned a fight with Anthony Joshua.  And AJ has a canny team behind him and pick and choose his fights on his capabilities . AJ is vulnerable, as he showed in his first fight with Ruiz. But that experience of being taken out by the inexperienced Ruiz he learned from and is a better boxer now, AJ is old school and has outstanding ringcraft that can only improve, can he beat Wilder or Fury yet? It is hard to say on the evidence so far. ?

At the end of the day, I do respect Wilder to a certain degree.
But what angers me i guess.... is the fact he has been around for so long, shouts his mouth off about wanting to be the very best in the world, how Joshua is apparently the one dodging and ducking, yet Wilder has never ventured out his pond, hasn't faced any real danger man.
Yet give Joshua his credit, he has faced any and all that has come his way.
When he lost his belts, he regrouped, reanalyzed, and came back stronger regaining his belts.
Now Wilder only has his one punch, that is it... he is not a great boxer.
But that one punch can end you.
If Joshua trained specifically for Wilder, didn't showboat, get cocky, and used a tactic like the Parker and Ruiz 2 fight, Wilder would know he was losing on points and would hopefully and literally windmill punching blowing himself out and leaving himself open for an AJ counter punch.
But by god, it would be a game plan he would HAVE to stick to religiously, one slip up and Wilder caught him with that shot, and it would be lights out and game over.
